{"_id":"4Lb1niy223K3b4XJ","name":"Caras Elvaren","content":"<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Official Name: </span></strong></span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Caras Elvaren</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Capital: </span></strong></span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Cathrach Talsien</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.25in;text-indent:-.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Official Head of State: </span></strong></span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">None</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.25in;text-indent:-.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">De Facto Heads of State: </span></strong></span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Gwetheir ap Wridd, Archmage of the Academy, Melianthe Cerunna, Speaker for the Assembly, and/or Brynmor, Princeps of House Meilyr, depending on who you ask.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.25in;text-indent:-.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Primary Inhabitants: </span></strong></span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Elves, trolls, gnomes</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.25in;text-indent:-.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Currency:</span></strong></span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\"> Statum (gp), obol (sp), morion (cp). Also drachma (electrum, 4 sp).</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\"> </span></strong></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Caras Elvaren is the nation that arose after the abandonment of Caras Seidharen during the Collapse. It began as an attempt to reform ancient elven society, keeping its general form while eliminating the rot which allowed the Sidhe to become tyrants. </span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\"> </span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt\">History</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Not all of the elves who lived through the Collapse chose to fade into obscurity in Tir Coetir. The remainder, many of whom were dissenters even before the Collapse, resolved to rebuild their civilization in the west, avoiding the failures of their former rulers.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Their new nation was named Caras Elvaren: loosely translated, “A Nation for the People.” Its society and government were built deliberately to deny the possibility of tyrants, particularly tyrants of a magical nature: the country has no central authority, and many provisions allowing the people to make their voices heard or restrain those in power.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">This was accompanied by a massive cultural shift: the high elves, as they came to be called, shunned sorcery and pacts with eldritch beings, which were common and prestigious forms of magic under the Sidhe. Instead, they turned to wizardry since—in theory—anyone could become a wizard with sufficient study. They were aided in this paradigm shift by Talsien, the legendary first wizard, who had been banished centuries earlier by the Sidhe. Talsien visited the high elves many times during the first few centuries of their new government (somehow not seeming to age during his absences), each time providing the elves with some new insight into magic. Talsien’s final visit occurred four centuries after the founding of Caras Elvaren, during which he gave his staff, wand, cloak, and spellbook to four of his apprentices—themselves wizards of great power—charging them with the preservation of Caras Elvaren from authoritarian rule.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">All of these anti-authoritarian measures succeeded, perhaps too well: the elves of Caras Elvaren have maintained a position of neutrality in foreign affairs for most of the last millennium, largely due to their government’s difficulty in reaching a consensus on foreign policy. </span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">On the few occasions when the high elves have engaged in diplomacy for more than routine trade agreements and affirmations of friendship, it has been to counsel against war and authoritarianism. Most notably, Caras Elvaren broke their policy of neutrality several times during the Wars of Smoke and Steel, threatening to ally with the losing sides in several wars, so that the wars would come to an end. The high elves were also the driving force behind the peace treaties which finally ended the Wars, and the establishment of the Concilium in an effort to prevent similarly destructive wars in the future. </span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\"> </span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt\">Politics</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">The government of Caras Elvaren is difficult to define, because there is so little of it: the nation was once described as “the closest one can get to anarchy, while still having something that resembles a government.” Outside observers largely concur that Caras Elvaren is a federation of free-associating anarcho-syndicalist cooperatives, although this holds little meaning for anyone who does not study politics.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">The core of Caras Elvaren’s government is the House, a formal association of citizens working toward a common purpose. The Houses originated as the households of aristocratic elves who escaped the Collapse, and were rapidly reformed to allow any group of citizens to form their own House. A House is permitted to claim a limited form of sovereignty over land which they own outright, and to send a representative to the National Assembly: in exchange, the House is required to perform services “suited to the skills of its members, and contributing to the common good” as determined by the National Assembly every ten years. Houses with many farmers may be required to provide food to the un-Housed, Houses that trade may be required to maintain roads or canals, and Houses with many wizards and artificers may be required to maintain the nation’s many magic-dependent public conveniences.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Houses commonly rise and fall within Caras Elvaren: those which succeed at their appointed functions are rewarded with prestige, as well as funding to take on more complicated or important functions. Those which fail due to negligence or incompetence are assessed fines and penalties, which can often drive members of a House to abandon it, leading to its disbanding. It is rare for a House to remain large and powerful for long: the anarchic leanings of the elves often cause powerful Houses to be saddled with increasingly onerous duties, until they eventually fail to meet their obligations and begin to decline. This creates turnover in the upper ranks of the Houses, preventing the rise of a permanent ruling class and allowing new factions opportunities to grow.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">A notable exception to this is the small number of military Houses which make up Caras Elvaren’s professional military: though they are essential to preserving the nation’s neutral stance, other Houses remain painfully aware that the standing army is one of a few remaining avenues for a would-be tyrant to take charge. The National Assembly therefore strikes a delicate balance when it comes to the military Houses: they are provided with a generous budget and given a prominent voice when it comes to matters of national defense—in exchange for staying out of politics.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\"> </span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt\">Society</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">In addition to performing the role of government, the Houses are also the center of society in Caras Elvaren. Some citizens join a House because it advocates for their causes in the Assembly. Others join a House because it offers work to people of their skills, or because the House’s reputation and connections open doors to them.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Most Houses are run on a vaguely democratic basis: since a House’s political power depends heavily on maintaining its membership, dictatorial Houses don’t tend to last long. Some Houses are simply comprised of an extended family, and are run by the family elders; others have aristocratic traditions in which the heirs of the founding members have a disproportionate say in the running of the House. Regardless of the exact organization, it is difficult for any House to maintain its membership if its leaders consistently make unpopular decisions. </span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">At any time, roughly two-thirds of citizens belong to a House, with many of the others being temporarily between Houses. However, there is a sizeable underclass of permanently un-Housed citizens: these are largely unskilled workers (by elven standards) who have nothing to contribute to a House, or those who are so exceptionally anti-authority that they decline to participate in the House system.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Because Houses claim sovereignty over their land, many disagreements and crimes are handled internally, or by mutual agreement between the Houses of criminal and victim. If no agreement can be reached, there are also neutral Houses which act as mediators due to the prevalence of legal theorists in their membership. On the rare occasion when even this does not resolve a dispute, the aggrieved Houses can seek a judgement from the National Assembly, but this is unusual, as it exposes both Houses’ private business to public view. </span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Some Houses claim territory outside of the borders of Caras Elvaren, ranging from ancient elven outposts and important ley-line conjunctions to simple shops and theaters in foreign countries. Their legal status can be complicated—as it is not always clear how a House’s sovereignty interacts with a host nation’s laws—but their host nations generally take a hands-off approach, treating these House enclaves as unofficial embassies or consulates.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">One especially notable House is the Academy of the Evanescent, Caras Elvaren’s oldest and most prominent school of wizardry. Founded by Talsien, the legendary original wizard, the Academy accepts students from any House and no House, on the sole condition that they transfer their House membership to the Academy for the duration of their education. This is one of the factors responsible for the remarkable stability of Caras Elvaren’s society and traditions: the Grand Masters of the Academy descend in an unbroken chain of apprenticeships from Talsien himself, and view it as their sworn duty to perpetuate the society that their forebear helped to build. Students at the Academy are inculcated with the traditional elven virtues: diligence, selflessness, and the endless search for inward perfection. As many of these students eventually return to prominent positions in their Houses of origin, or go on to found their own, the Academy quietly ensures the continuity of elven philosophy in the halls of power.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Because of the Academy and other schools of magic, Caras Elvaren possesses vastly more arcanists in the population than any other nation. As a result, the entire nation is steeped in magic. A breakthrough two centuries ago led to the construction of ley line taps—vast mechanisms capable of drawing and harnessing power from the ley lines running beneath the earth. The taps generate a magical field around them, capable of powering all manner of magical devices from automated farm equipment to labor golems—and the taps are everywhere. Very few elves perform manual labor or get their hands dirty in the traditional sense: the “working class” in Caras Elvaren now consists of technicians who know how to maintain and direct these magical tools. The elves are loath to share the plans or theories behind the ley-line taps, partly because of the advantage it gives them—but also because the devices can be horrendously destructive if miscalibrated. The taps are Caras Elvaren’s strength and weakness at the same time, for they are what grant the elves their power—but each one is also a bomb waiting to go off.</span></span></p>","img":null,"folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"hsFJxrWN4M5Ezw3L":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.aetrimonde_v0_8_x.aetrimonde-setting.4Lb1niy223K3b4XJ"},"cf":{"id":"temp_i4cc68g5ub","path":"The World of Aetrimonde#/CF_SEP/Major Polities","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"4PO4Dt2uWHKhq9ic","name":"The Free Cities","content":"<p>The Free Cities are a trio of independent and relatively young city-states (and their surrounding territories) that associate with each other only due to their geographical closeness. Two of them broke away from the Novan Imperium during the Wars of Smoke and Steel, while the Imperium was occupied fighting both the Sanctean Primarchy and border raiders from Tir Coetir. For the city of Staccarsi, the secession was because of its peoples' sincerely-held ideals of democracy, self-determination, and mortal rights, while for the city of Libertino, it was because monied interests in the city saw an opportunity to stop paying the imperial taxes. </p>\n<p>The third city, King's Fall, was formerly part of the Petty Kingdoms, until it came under the rule of an especially quixotic and foolish would-be king. When the inevitable peasant uprising occurred, the king lost his head first figuratively, and then literally. The uprising by this time had gained enough momentum that it spiraled out of control, turning first on the remaining nearby nobles, then on the intellectual and merchant classes, and finally on itself as different factions of the revolution declared each other to be backsliders. A \"Citizens' Committee for Public Order\" has risen from the ashes of the revolution, and although it has been working to wipe out or rein in the last active revolutionaries for five years now, it remains to be seen whether it will succeed in restoring some semblance of normalcy to the city.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"txsdYu7V4ixj4DHp":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_w4yki4y5ebj","path":"The World of Aetrimonde#/CF_SEP/Minor Polities","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"554z6SUV15AGVUG1","name":"Novan Imperium","content":"<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Official Name: </span></strong></span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Aureos Secundum Imperium (The Second Auran Empire)</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Capital: </span></strong></span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Arx Novum</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.25in;text-indent:-.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Head of State: </span></strong></span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Marcus Gaius Antonius Imperator.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.25in;text-indent:-.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Primary Inhabitants: </span></strong></span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Humans, orcs</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.25in;text-indent:-.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Currency:</span></strong></span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\"> Solidii (gp), sestertii (sp), denarii (cp)</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\"> </span></strong></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">The Novan Empire is a successor-state to the ancient Auran Empire. Founded by remnants of the Auran legions after the collapse, the Imperium is a regimented, orderly society which retains many cultural ties to humanity’s first great civilization.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\"> </span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt\">History</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">In the ancient days of the Age of Glory, humanity spread across the known world, and many cultures emerged from the diaspora. Yet, there was one civilization which rose above all others: that of Arcis Aurum, the Golden Citadel.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Arcis Aurum eventually fell, during the Collapse, but at its height it was said that one could walk down any road and eventually reach the Golden Citadel, that the monumental buildings were faced with gold, and that its kings were fair and wise, concerned above all else with the good of their people.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">The truth is probably less fanciful, but Legate Gaius Julius Valerius, the general of a Legion which rode out the Collapse in a remote mountainous outpost, drew upon the legends when he set out to reclaim the ruins of humanity’s glorious civilization. During his lifetime, his fledgling empire grew from a fortified mining town to encompass dozens of towns and nearly a million souls. He accomplished this by forcibly annexing every population center within a hundred miles, conscripting every able-bodied human into his Legion, and enslaving most of the non-humans to toil in the fields and mines. It was a campaign of ruthless, imperialistic expansion, but by the time of his death, Emperor Gaius had laid the groundwork for a stable, prosperous state amid the ruins of civilization. </span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Gaius’ son and grandson, Gaius II and Gaius III (for none of the Valerian Emperors were especially original thinkers) built on this foundation: Gaius II exterminated or enslaved the last of the orcs near the territories of the Novan Imperium, and Gaius III continued to expand the borders until they neared the ruins of Arcis Aurum itself. However, Gaius III’s inevitable attempt to retake the heavily orc-infested ruins put an end to the expansionary plans of the Gaian emperors.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">After the first attempt to claim the city failed, causing the near-destruction of two Legions, Gaius III declared his intent to reinstitute universal conscription, a practice which had stopped in his father’s reign. The citizens of the Novan Imperium had grown prosperous and complacent, however, and the return of conscription sparked rebellions in several important cities. </span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">After the enraged Gaius III marched his Legions upon the nearest rebelling city and burned it to the ground, his officers mutinied and assassinated him. Afterwards, the governor of the Arcis Novis, the Imperial capitol, was placed on the throne thanks to a document in which Gaius III had adopted the governor as his heir. The document was likely a forgery, but in the aftermath of the recent rebellions, mutiny, and regicide, few people bothered to question it. </span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Similar events played out after two more attempts to recapture Arcis Aurum during the next three centuries: each time, elements of the Imperial government conspired to replace the fixated Emperor, until, after the final failed attempt, the newly-crowned Empress Juliana Augusta Antonia decreed that the ruins of Arcis Aurum be left as they were, “as a memorial to humanity’s ancient glory.”</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Empress Juliana also formally established the structure of the permanent Novan civil service, instituting a regimen of policies, procedures, offices, and qualifying examinations designed to ensure that the Empire was run by the best minds possible. Additionally, Juliana ceded some of her absolute authority to the newly-created bureaucracy, allowing them to perform day-to-day administrative functions without her input. Perhaps not coincidentally, many of the high-ranking administrators in her new civil service had supported her rise to the throne.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">With its expansionary tendencies quelled, the Novan Imperium turned its attentions inward: the nation prospered as scholars rediscovered lost knowledge of engineering, medicine, and magic, and then moved beyond it into new areas of discovery. The Novans gradually abolished the practice of slavery and began to grant citizenship to non-humans, eventually gaining a large population of loyal orc and dwarf citizens.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">The Novan Imperium began the known world’s industrial revolution with the invention of the steam engine—a device invented by exiled dwarves using Novan funding—and continued to develop mechanical technology. Today, the Novan Imperium is at the forefront of industrial and mechanical engineering, and its engineers and arcanists have begun to experiment with machinery powered by “harnessed lightning.” The most prominent of these experiments has been the creation of the telectrograph, a device for passing messages over great distances using carefully-modulated bolts of lightning: relays of telectrograph towers now connect the world’s great capitals, and are expanding into less populated regions as well.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt\"> </span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt\">Politics</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">The Novan Imperium is sometimes described as an autocracy, sometimes as a meritocracy, and sometimes as a senatorial republic. In truth, it is all of these, but it is best described as a bureaucracy.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">In theory, the Emperor (or Imperator) is an absolute dictator, but he relies upon a massive and unwieldy civil service to enforce his edicts. It is slow to implement any but the most urgent or universally acclaimed decrees, and over time, the Emperors and Empresses have gradually ceded much of their authority to various offices and bureaus, since they would likely do whatever they pleased anyway. Although in theory the Emperors may appoint any successor they like from among their family, for the last two centuries they have abided by selections made by a council of high-ranking administrators.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">The civil service has a strong meritocratic tradition: any citizen of the Imperium who performs a job which is useful to society, and does it well, may find themselves promoted into a position of responsibility. Usually, this works out well: knowledgeable farmers end up on councils which set agricultural subsidies, miners wind up overseeing safety inspections, and so on. However, this makes the Novan government slow to implement “unnecessary” changes: many artists, craftsmen and engineers appointed to positions of responsibility fall back to what they know, neglecting new innovations. Styles of art, architecture, and even the Novan language have stagnated as a result.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">There is also a great degree of de-facto nepotism among the bureaucracy: although there are rigorous entrance examinations for the higher ranks of the civil service, many bureaucrats groom their children to follow them into the civil service, enrolling them in prestigious academies and offering insider knowledge to help them pass the exams. Many smaller offices, that attract less competition and fewer inspections, have been held by a single family for generations.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">The only branch of the Imperial government which does not suffer from this bureaucratic inertia is the military: the Novan Legions remain under the direct control of the Emperor, and they are often employed as a means to cut through red tape: the legion’s engineers, quartermasters, and clerks can be tapped to do double-duty as civilian administrators when the bureaucrats of a particular province are being especially obstructive, and previous Emperors have even sent Legions to forcibly remove governors and their staffs from office.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Emperor Marcus Gaius Antonius is a young Emperor, less than a decade into office. His reign has been uneventful: outside observers await his first political crisis, which will reveal whether he remains content to let his civil servants run the Empire, or if he will take a more active role.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt\"> </span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt\">Society</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Private citizens in the Novan Imperium—those without ties to the civil service—can be grouped into three classes: </span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Plebeians are the miners who fuel the Novan industrial juggernaut, laborers who work in its foundries and factories, and the farmers who keep it fed. The farmers are most fortunate, for life is far easier in the countryside than in the crowded, soot-choked cities. Urban plebes are kept satisfied by free food and public entertainment, such as spectacles in the amphitheater: these once featured frequent gladiatorial games, before the abolition of slavery, and there are still occasional death matches between theoretically-consenting combatants.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Fabricians are the inventors, engineers, and captains of industry who direct the Novan economy. It is they who design, develop and market new processes and technologies: the class structure was less defined when the first steam engine was built, but its creators would today be counted as fabricians. The fabricians are also responsible for advances such as the telectrograph—a means of sending messages great distances on bolts of lightning—and the railway.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Cognoscenti are the learned—some would say idle—class of Novan society. Many are artists, for the demand for bread and circuses means that there is always funding for an artist who can mimic the politically-approved styles. Others are intellectuals, including many arcanists who prefer to spend their efforts on theoretical research: those who put their magic to productive use are usually counted among the Fabricians.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Religion is less common in the Imperium than in the other major powers: the Imperium struggles with a variety of cults—a legacy of the chaos and despair felt in Arcis Aurum during the Collapse—and more recently, suffered through a period of religious turmoil during the rise of the Sanctean Primarchy. As a result, many Novans hold a distrust of organized religion, if not religion in general. Priests who engage in politics or are too eager to show off divine magic often find themselves shunned, or even subjected to investigation by the secular authorities.</span></span></p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"hsFJxrWN4M5Ezw3L":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.aetrimonde_v0_8_x.aetrimonde-setting.554z6SUV15AGVUG1"},"cf":{"id":"temp_i4cc68g5ub","path":"The World of Aetrimonde#/CF_SEP/Major Polities","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"6JKMmowwdFdnJXD8","name":"Stormbreak Bay","content":"<p>Stormbreak Bay is a large bay, almost an inland sea, sheltered from the worst storms blowing off of the Storm-Wracked Sea. The bay would be ideal for maritime trade, were it not for the fact that most of the ports on it belong to either Victovy or Waystone, nations with a longstanding rivalry. As it is, Victovy controls the northern passage into the bay and effectively bars passage to ships flying Waystone's flag by levying exorbitant port and pilotage fees. Most of Waystone's maritime trade passes through the narrow Windefrake Strait at the south of the bay; this creates such a stream of shipping that Waystone, and the governments of the Salvage Coast, are considering whether it would be practical to widen the Strait with explosives to relieve the congestion.</p>\n<p>The bay is also home to significant smuggling activity: much of this is simply illicit commerce (such as attempts to bring valuable goods into Waystone without paying the Crown's import duties), but given the political tensions among Victovy, Waystone, and the city-states of the Buffer Zone, there are more clandestine enterprises afoot. Small ships frequently make the crossing under cover of night carrying intelligence agents and dispatches, and there is a steady stream of political dissidents fleeing Victovy ahead of the Tsareva's secret police as well as banned materials and substances going the other way to supply various revolutionaries and anarchists.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"txsdYu7V4ixj4DHp":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_aixisdz1brv","path":"The World of Aetrimonde#/CF_SEP/Bodies of Water","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"6Jojzq37NNNlrFK3","name":"The Unclaimed Reaches","content":"<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">To the south of Waystone, the land grows hot and dry: between the poor soil and a lack of important mineral resources, none of the great nations have ever had much interest in colonizing or claiming the area. Instead, a few stubborn homesteaders and prospectors scratch a living out of the dust. Recently, though, a few of those prospectors have hit rich deposits of gold and other precious metals, attracting miners and merchants, as well as outlaws and robber barons. It is a lawless region, where justice is only found at the point of a sword or the barrel of a gun. </span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\">The city of Hayward's Point is the southernmost bastion of civilization in the Reaches; its proximity to Waystone and Caras Elvaren gives it some protection from the bandits and warlords that run rampant further south, and the railroad spur connecting the city to Waystone means that a handful of merchant houses have established outposts there. The city has become a jumping-off point for prospectors heading further into the Reaches to seek their fortunes, as well as adventurers on their way to explore the goblin ruins far to the south. This is not to say that Hayward's Point is a safe place; many a prospector or adventurer has lost their finds (and their life) to an opportunist with a gun in one of the city's dusty alleyways.</p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\">A handful of coastal towns in the far south of the Reaches offer safe harbors for ships on their way around the southern tip of the continent; these are no great shipping ports, merely a few buildings that have grown up around a sheltered cove or inlet. From time to time, when prospectors find a rich vein of minerals or an unexplored goblin ruin nearby, these towns turn into hives of activity as miners and adventurers flock to them, only to return to their slow decline as soon as the finds are depleted.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":2,"hsFJxrWN4M5Ezw3L":3,"lh2XdhvmO8rwUMvb":2},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.aetrimonde_v0_8_x.aetrimonde-setting.6Jojzq37NNNlrFK3"},"cf":{"id":"temp_jtqi9qh2rjq","path":"The World of Aetrimonde#/CF_SEP/Unincorporated Territories","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"7lus652hNGxfNa40","name":"Der Eisenwald","content":"<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">The Eisenwald is a forested, hilly region located between Victovy, the Ironspine Mountains, and the borderlands of Urku. The land is rich in natural resources, and would normally attract Victovan annexation, were it not for the inhabitants: the myriad towns and villages nestled in the Eisenwald are ruled by a motley collection of mad scientists and deranged magicians, who flock to the region as a place where they can pursue their strange experiments, construct doomsday devices, and plot world domination in peace. Given the unruly and unpredictable nature of the locals, the Victs, the dwarves, and even the nearby orc marauders give the region a wide berth.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">The city of Umpf is the cultural center of Der Eisenwald, and a neutral ground ruled by an elected town council instead of the monsters and madmen who rule the rest of the region. The city's famed markets trade in all manner of magic and science that is banned or regulated elsewhere, and there are even a handful of schools that promise to teach the secrets of dark magic and obscure science, but the council cracks down hard on anyone whose commercial or academic endeavors threaten to break the peace.</span></span></p>","img":null,"folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":2,"hsFJxrWN4M5Ezw3L":3,"lh2XdhvmO8rwUMvb":2},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.aetrimonde_v0_8_x.aetrimonde-setting.7lus652hNGxfNa40"},"cf":{"id":"temp_w4yki4y5ebj","path":"The World of Aetrimonde#/CF_SEP/Minor Polities","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"82UZR6UUiq20FU37","name":"Waystone","content":"<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Official Name: </span></strong></span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">The Chartered Kingdom of Waystone</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Capital:</span></strong></span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\"> The City of Waystone</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.25in;text-indent:-.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Head of State: </span></strong></span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Her Majesty, Helena II of the House of Lynton, by grace of the Gods Monarch of Waystone and its environs, Empress of the Dunfealdie Highlands and the Drowned Coast, and Defender of the Protectorates.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.25in;text-indent:-.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Primary Inhabitants: </span></strong></span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Diverse</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.25in;text-indent:-.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Currency:</span></strong></span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\"> Crowns (gp), shillings (sp) and pence (cp). Also pounds (platinum, 6gp), half-guineas (gold, 3gp + 1sp + 5cp), baker’s shillings (electrum, 1sp + 3cp), tupney bits (iron, 2cp) and many, many other strange denominations.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.25in;text-indent:-.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"font-size:18.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt\"> </span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Waystone is a small but influential nation centered on the city of Waystone, from which the country takes its name. The city is, by a wide margin, the largest in the known world, but the rest of the country contains no settlement larger than a mid-sized town. </span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Waystone is small, compared to the other Great Powers, but maintains a position among them by virtue of its vast mercantile network, diplomatic ties to many smaller nations, and highly competent spies and special forces.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\"> </span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt\">History</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Long before the founding of Waystone, the territory it now occupies was home to many bands of nomadic halflings, who travelled its rolling hills and gentle rivers in caravans and on riverboats. Sadly, the growing power of Gobol Karn, to the south, saw the end of this way of life: as slaver raids became more frequent, almost all halflings fled to the north or found remote valleys in which to hide.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">This state of affairs persisted for centuries, until the decline of Gobol Karn 80 years before the general collapse of civilization at the end of the Age of Tyrants. Following the collapse, as human, elf and dwarf refugees fled west in advance of the oncoming orc horde, they encountered halflings just returning to their ancestral lands. The two groups of settlers, after some initial distrust, agreed to cooperate in securing the lands around what is now called the Lake of the Signing. Some years later, the leaders of the now-prospering refugees signed the First Charter on a great, ancient standing stone at the edge of the lake, and Heomund Lynton became the first King of Waystone by popular acclaim.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">In the eight centuries since, the Kings and Queens of Waystone have turned their nation into an economic powerhouse by exploiting the many rivers feeding into and out of the Lake of the Signing, and later by constructing canals crossing much of the western part of the continent. Vast quantities of freight move through this network and on Waystone’s merchant fleet, and the Crown takes its share of taxes on every ounce of it.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">At the beginning of the Wars of Smoke and Steel, nearly a century ago, the Victovan Empire began to expand southward, annexing its smaller neighbors. As the richest nation in their path, it was only a matter of time before the Victs turned their sights on Waystone.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">To survive in the face of Victovan aggression, Waystone used two strategies: first, Waystone built a phenomenally effective intelligence network using its mercantile and political connections across the continent. Using this network, Waystone was able to funnel information, money, and materiel to the targets of Victovan imperialism. This only slowed the Victovan advance, but it bought time for Waystone to build up its forces and develop strategies using newly-developed magics.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">When the Victovan Empire finally declared war, they saw the products of these investments. The Royal Marines, using teleportation circles planted by Waystone’s spy networks, struck far behind enemy lines, destroying crucial Victovan factories, supply depots, and garrisons within days of the outbreak of hostilities. As the war dragged on, Waystone continued to support resistance groups in Victovy’s occupied territory, providing them with the same equipment and training used by the Marines to such great effect. Eventually, faced with a spreading insurgency, and an enemy that they could not engage in decisive battles, Victovy accepted a ceasefire and abandoned many of its occupied territories.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Waystone continues to ally with minor nations, offering access to its mercantile contacts, intelligence networks, and even military training, in exchange for mutual-defense pacts. There are dozens of these minor allies scattered around the known world—some of them no larger than city-states—but thanks to Waystone’s mastery of teleportation magic, each one of them is capable of coming to aid the others almost immediately, and most of them have armies trained almost to the standard of the Royal Marines. In this way, Waystone is counted among the other great powers despite their smaller size. Much like the wood elves of Tir Coetir, they have arranged matters so that any attempt to conquer them would result in a pyrrhic victory at best—and though their treaties technically only provide for mutual defense, there is little doubt that if Waystone decided to go to war, most of the Protectorates would follow. </span></span></p>\n<p><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA\"> </span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt\">Politics</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Waystone is a constitutional monarchy, with the powers of the monarch tempered by the laws set down in the Charter of Waystone.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">The Charter has been amended repeatedly since it was originally written, including two major revisions: Waystone’s history is divided into eras between these revisions, and the three eras are referred to as the First, Second, and Third Charters.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">The First Charter established a hereditary nobility, and simultaneously placed limits on the powers of these nobles. The Charter also placed a King at the head of the nobility, but placed the selection of the King in the hands of the people: following the signing of the First Charter, Heomund Lynton was elevated to the throne by popular vote, and the remaining nobles became his councilors in the House of Lords.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">The Second Charter, amended two centuries after the Founding, granted the power of the Exchequer—the power to levy taxes and control expenditures—to the House of Lords so that it might act as a counterweight to the reigning monarch. It also established a House of Commons, which took over the role of councilors to the Crown, but had no official authority. Members of the House of Commons were originally appointed by the House of Lords, resulting in a membership which didn’t truly reflect the will of the people.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">The Third Charter, written a mere two decades ago, was a reaction to a constitutional crisis provoked by the death of King Edmund and the appointment of a corrupt regent until then-Princess Helena came of age. Regent Blackwood, with support from the House of Lords, removed many checks against the abuse of aristocratic power, leading to the oppression of Waystone’s lower and middle classes. After Helena II’s ascent to the throne—having marched on Parliament and overthrown Regent Blackwood at the head of a mob—the Third Charter granted the House of Commons the legislative powers formerly held by the Crown, and established elections to appoint the members of Parliament.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">In theory, Helena II is now a mere figurehead, having relinquished almost all of the powers of the Crown. However, she holds the loyalty of the common people of Waystone, and her supporters command an overwhelming majority in the House of Commons. The only obstacle to her agenda is the House of Lords, which still maintains control over the Treasury.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Waystone’s intelligence apparatus—the Royal Intelligencers, or Queen’s Eyes—is well-funded and frighteningly effective, to the point that Waystone’s diplomats no longer bother to pretend that they aren’t spying on their allies and rivals. Countless plots and intrigues have been derailed when an ambassador from Waystone showed up unannounced with a folder full of evidence—and there are an unknown number of plots that succeeded because someone in Waystone decided to lend a helping hand behind the scenes. The Intelligencers are also known to perform assassinations, kidnappings, and other unsavory actions if required—but they have a code of honor, of sorts, which considers such skullduggery inelegant and ungentlemanly.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\"> </span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt\">Society</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Waystone is essentially two cultures, separated by a deep divide. On one hand, there is the City of Waystone itself, a metropolis unrivaled by any other in the known world, where people of all nations mingle and collaborate. On the other, there are the outlying regions (sometimes called the Environs), home to small farming communities and rural estates.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Life in the capital is vibrant and fast-paced: people are packed closely together, due to a perpetual shortage of land and housing, and it is difficult to go even a single block without hearing at least three languages or dialects. The City’s markets overflow with goods from around the world, brought in by Waystone’s merchant fleet, and buyers can find anything they might seek—for the right price. Prosperous merchants in the City buy and sell vast quantities of goods—often while the goods themselves are still half a world away, thanks to conveniences such as <em style=\"mso-bidi-font-style:normal\">visitation</em> rituals and the telectrogram.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">By contrast, the Environs are laid-back and insular: the economy there revolves around farming—mostly to feed the millions of mouths in the City, although Waystone still relies heavily on imports from the Protectorates. Waystone’s farmers also grow a few other crops, mostly for the textile industry, and many rural farmers are quietly prosperous in their own way. Rural lords and members of Parliament usually spend winters in the City in order to fulfill their governmental duties and attend the obligatory social events, returning to the countryside as soon as the rivers thaw in the spring.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">The two cultures of Waystone often profess some derision for each other: the cityfolk view their rural cousins as backwards bumpkins, while the countryfolk consider inhabitants of the City foolish and greedy. Much of this rivalry is tongue-in-cheek: it’s quite common for rural youths to move to the City seeking their fortunes, and for City merchants to retire to farms in the country after their ventures pay off. That said, there have been clashes in the past, over issues of taxation, land-use policy, and social programs, where Parliament is thought to favor wealthy City interests.</span></span></p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"hsFJxrWN4M5Ezw3L":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.aetrimonde_v0_8_x.aetrimonde-setting.82UZR6UUiq20FU37"},"cf":{"id":"temp_i4cc68g5ub","path":"The World of Aetrimonde#/CF_SEP/Major Polities","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"9jHSXk8Wo6rkln01","name":"Dwarven Federation","content":"<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Official Name: </span></strong></span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Dvergarbandalagið (lit. The Dwarven Federation)</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Formal Capital: </span></strong></span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Konigstrond (destroyed).</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">De Facto Capital: </span></strong></span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Hasaeti-af-Tapi.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.25in;text-indent:-.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Official Head of State: </span></strong></span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">High King Torgrim III Unbowed (deceased).</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.25in;text-indent:-.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">De Facto Head of State: </span></strong></span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Ingmar Ingvaldssen, Thane of Clan Volsung, Regent for the Unclaimed Throne.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.25in;text-indent:-.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Primary Inhabitants: </span></strong></span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Dwarves</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.25in;text-indent:-.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Currency:</span></strong></span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\"> Kroner (gp), ore (sp), kopar (cp)</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\"> </span></strong></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">The Dwarven Federation is a loose association of the many dwarven clans spread throughout the Ironspine Mountains. The throne of the dwarves, in the ruined royal city of Konigstrond, has remained empty for nine centuries, ever since the fall of the High King and the likely extinction of his line during the Collapse: the Regent, elected from among the often-quarrelling thanes of the clans, acts partly as a figurehead, and partly as a scapegoat when things go wrong.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\"> </span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"font-size:14.0pt\">History</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Prior to the Collapse, when the elves and humans were at each other’s’ throats, the dwarves remained neutral—even disinterested. They sold weapons to each side, of course, and they appeared in force whenever the fighting strayed too close to their borders, but by and large they ignored the conflict. When the orcs surged out of the east, the dwarves still remained aloof—so when the orcs overran Caras Seidharen and Arcis Aurum, the dwarves were able to meet the weakened horde with their full might.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Even this proved insufficient in the face of the orcs’ savagery: falling back from their eastern borders, the dwarves resorted to luring the orcs towards their heavily-fortified capital, Konigstrond. There, they forced the orcs to fight their way inch-by-inch up the mountainside, until at last they broke through into the royal palace at the mountain’s peak.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">It is unclear what precisely happened when the orcs at last entered the High King’s throne room—but shortly afterward, the mountain was shaken by a great tremor, causing the entire face of the mountain to collapse and bury the bulk of the orc horde. The horde was at long last broken, but of High King Torgrim and his heirs and retainers, there was no sign. </span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">The loss of their king—and of their culture’s greatest repositories of knowledge, history, and treasure—left the dwarven nation sundered. The many clans, once united behind their High King, withdrew into their mountain fastnesses to regain their strength, and wait out the shattered remnants of the orc horde. When they emerged again, a century later, the dwarves were no longer a single people, but a collection of fractious, uncooperative clans. Grievances that had festered for a hundred years boiled over, and the dwarves threatened to make war upon each other.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">This battle was forestalled by Olaf, Thane of Clan Ulfenning, and then one of the oldest dwarves alive: Olaf produced the crown of the High King, which he claimed to have discovered during the retreat from Konigstrond, some ways from the site of the battle. Its presence there meant that Torgrim, or a member of his family, must have escaped from the battle alive—and thus, claimed Olaf, the dwarves were honor-bound to preserve the kingdom until the rightful High King could be found and placed on the throne.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">This was a justification which allowed the gathered dwarves to set aside their quarrels without breaking oaths or losing face. And so it was that Olaf of Clan Ulfenning was acclaimed as the first Regent for the Unclaimed Throne, and the dwarves set about rebuilding their once-great nation.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">The dwarves soon discovered just how much they had lost in the Collapse: many of the great secrets of their ancestors had been jealously guarded in the archives of Konigstrond and lost with the city. They no longer knew the formulas and methods for smelting mithril or adamantine, or many of the runes of power, and much of their history, genealogy, and other records were long-lost. As they realized that they might never reach the heights of their former glory, the dwarves clung all the more tightly to what they still possessed: the relics and fragments of lore which had escaped Konigstrond became treasured artifacts held in trust for all dwarfkind, and when Regent Olaf died—at an astonishing old age, even for a dwarf—he was declared the first of many Venerated Ancestors: dwarves who embodied the lost glory of their race, and examples to all those who would follow.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Little has changed in the Dwarven Federation since then: the dwarves continue to seek out scraps of their lost history and clues as to their rightful king, but this means that they have stagnated over the course of almost a millennium, while humanity and even the elves have moved on. Innovators and inventors face an uphill battle among the dwarves, since the knowledge and creations of the ancestors are considered the pinnacle of dwarven excellence—and replacing the work of an ancestor is considered offensive, even blasphemous, to their descendants. The dwarves still have not rediscovered how their ancestors smelted adamantine (though they have figured out mithril), and many of their great works of engineering still cannot be replicated, even as they fall into disrepair. </span></span></p>\n<p><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"font-size:14.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA\"> </span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"font-size:14.0pt\">Politics</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">In the absence of the rightful High King, the dwarves are ruled by a council of Thanes—the rulers of powerful clans. Membership in the council varies, but for most of its history the council has consisted of between five and twelve Thanes. The Thanes elect a Regent from among their number, who serves until they lose the confidence of their peers. This Regent is considered a first among equals, with the power to negotiate for the collected clans of the Federation when dealing with outsiders and to issue edicts which have the force of law within the Federation, but as they can be overruled by a simple majority on the council, most Regents exercise this power sparingly.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">New Thanes can be elevated to the council by the acclamation of their would-be peers: this is generally taken to mean that the Thanes currently seated on the council must welcome the new member unanimously. Other decisions of significance also require unanimity, although when there is only a single dissenting vote, the matter is sometimes settled by expelling the dissenter from the council so that the vote becomes unanimous.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Clans whose Thane does not sit on the council can gain representation by pledging fealty to a sitting Thane; in practice this is almost automatic, because when new clans are founded, their founder generally swears fealty to their former Thane. In this manner, most of the clans currently in existence “descend” from one of the seven clans originally seated on the council. Clans are also known to shift their fealty, although it is a step which is not taken lightly: it occurs most often with the permission of a clan’s former liege, when all agree that the subordinate clan would be better represented by a different Thane. Less often, a clan changes its allegiance when they feel that their liege has dishonored them in some way; in such cases, the shift of fealty is often followed by the offending Thane being expelled from the council.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Clans control lands within the Ironspine Mountains, although the extent of clans’ territory varies widely: the largest territories consist of vast stretches of the mountains, while the smallest may only hold a few buildings where a clan lives and works. The size of a clan’s territory is only loosely related to the size, prestige or power of the clan; many powerful clans are simply uninterested in the work necessary to police and maintain large tracts of land, choosing instead to focus on other projects. A clan is naturally expected to defend its territory from invaders and lawbreakers; as such, many of the clans which control large areas are those with many warriors.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\"> </span></span></p>\n<p><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"font-size:14.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA\"> </span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"font-size:14.0pt\">Society</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Clans are of course the center of dwarven culture: members of a clan work closely with each other, and as a rule they also live, feast, celebrate, and worship together as well.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">A clan is more than just an extended family: it is also an enterprise. Every clan has something which they do for a living: stereotypical clans are miners, metalworkers, engineers, or jewelers, but there are also clans which farm, excavate ancient ruins, operate museums, or interpret the (extremely complicated) dwarven legal code. </span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Being born into a clan does not dictate what a dwarf does with their life, however. Though many dwarves choose to take up the family trade as a way of honoring their ancestors, a dwarf who has no interest in or talent for the clan’s business may seek entry into a clan which is more suitable for them—with permission from the Thanes of both clans, naturally. Marriage does not require a change of clan (and young dwarves are strongly discouraged from marrying within their clan, to make sure that they aren’t marrying a relative): children are permitted to join either of their parents’ clans when they come of age.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">To found a new clan, a dwarf must first receive permission from their Thane—who does not have to seek permission from anyone else, strictly speaking, but it is considered wise to get the approval of a Thane on the council before doing so. This permission is generally granted in recognition of some great accomplishment, although it is sometimes used to resolve schisms within a clan, by allowing a disgruntled faction to strike out on their own.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">A clan venerates its ancestors, especially the clan’s founder. This status is bestowed by a clan’s Stonekeeper—a position not unlike a priest, although dwarves seldom see it that way. The Stonekeepers keep records of every clan member’s notable acts—for good or for ill—and, upon a dwarf’s death, their clan’s Stonekeeper consults the records of their life to determine their worthiness—some might say dwarfishness. Only a small minority of dwarves achieve the status of Venerated Ancestor and are immortalized in stone, although few dwarves are relegated to obscurity: most simply have their deeds written down in stone and preserved in their clan’s records. To be struck from the records entirely—doomed to be forgotten by their descendants, as dwarves see it—is a shameful fate reserved only for those who commit some grave transgression.</span></span></p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"hsFJxrWN4M5Ezw3L":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.aetrimonde_v0_8_x.aetrimonde-setting.9jHSXk8Wo6rkln01"},"cf":{"id":"temp_i4cc68g5ub","path":"The World of Aetrimonde#/CF_SEP/Major Polities","color":"#000000"}}}
