{"_id":"FhzTM8KGLKM6zxFg","name":"The Gulf of Lost Hopes","content":"<p>The Gulf of Lost Hopes is sheltered from the worst of the storms blowing out of the west, and yet is the site of more shipwrecks than any other waters surrounding Kaern. The only port of note on the Gulf is Porte au Reine, and the Petty Kingdoms are not an attractive market for merchant ships. Rather than hugging the coast, many merchants attempt to cut directly across the Gulf and around the Cape of Corsairs to the richer markets of the east, and when a powerful storm does blow across the continent and into the Gulf, it results in many a sinking.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"txsdYu7V4ixj4DHp":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_aixisdz1brv","path":"The World of Aetrimonde#/CF_SEP/Bodies of Water","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"IMCihGVC4ATYNV6L","name":"The Petty Kingdoms","content":"<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Not all of the refugees who fled west during the Collapse made it as far as Waystone. Some, fleeing along the coastline, settled near elven outposts which had been abandoned in the flight to Caras Elvaren. The outposts contained caches of dearly-needed supplies, but also concealed dangerous artifacts and tomes of magical lore: many would-be tyrants among the refugees used them to become warlords or sorcerer-kings, terrorizing the region with poorly-understood magic, out-of-control summoned monsters, and armories of magical weaponry. For a brief period two centuries later, the Kingdoms were united by a popular king, Lucien Castesse, who had the backing of a competent and benevolent court wizard going only by the name of \"Myrthynn.\" Sadly, King Castesse died without issue, and despite Myrthynn's best efforts, the Kingdoms were once again torn apart as various lords and generals vied to claim the succession, a state which continues to this day.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\">Because of the divided nature of the Petty Kingdoms, there is no real capital. Virtually every town of even moderate size is claimed as the seat of some contender for the throne, and the inevitable wars and sieges tend to take a toll on large cities. The historic capital of the Kingdoms, from the brief period that the region was united under the rule of King Castesse, was Maletoc, which has fallen on hard times in the modern day. At present, three cities can claim to be the de facto capital:</p>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Kingsmarket, a center of trade with the elves of Caras Elvaren and Tir Coetir, ruled by the wealthy King Perenelde.</li>\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Port au Reine, the Kingdoms' major port city, and the seat of power for the manipulative Queen Caethrenne.</li>\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\">Pont du Chevalier, a central crossroads, undergoing a military buildup under an upstart warlord using the <em>nom de guerre </em>\"The Iron Duke.\"</li>\n</ul>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":2,"hsFJxrWN4M5Ezw3L":3,"lh2XdhvmO8rwUMvb":2},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.aetrimonde_v0_8_x.aetrimonde-setting.IMCihGVC4ATYNV6L"},"cf":{"id":"temp_w4yki4y5ebj","path":"The World of Aetrimonde#/CF_SEP/Minor Polities","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"JL1PBgn4wzZSICC0","name":"The Frigid Wastes","content":"<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Far to the north, where the sun sets for weeks at a time in winter, lie the Frigid Wastes: icy steppes too cold to grow much in the way of crops, and frozen islands barely more than spits of rock. It is an inhospitable land, but that attracts people who want to escape watchful eyes: in particular, it is an excellent place for cults and illicit arcanists such as diablerists and necromancers to gain a foothold. Many of the islands off the northern coast are claimed by occultists of one kind or another, and the few scattered towns in the Wastes often hold dark secrets which are a danger to the unwary traveler.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\">Brass Monkey, the largest town in the Wastes, was originally founded by a company of dwarven journeyman engineers. Unwilling to work within the strict confines of dwarven engineering tradition (mainly the taboo against modifying the work of anyone else's ancestors), they exploited a loophole and became shipbuilders. As no dwarf engineer had ever spent much time on such an endeavor, this freed them to innovate as they saw fit. The town is now a de facto colony of the Dwarven Federation, although it is far less traditional than the Federation proper, and is home to several shipyards specializing in the construction of ironclad steamships. One of their recent innovations is the \"icebreaker,\" a massively-reinforced and armored vessel capable of smashing through the sea ice of an arctic winter.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":2,"hsFJxrWN4M5Ezw3L":3,"lh2XdhvmO8rwUMvb":2},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.aetrimonde_v0_8_x.aetrimonde-setting.JL1PBgn4wzZSICC0"},"cf":{"id":"temp_jtqi9qh2rjq","path":"The World of Aetrimonde#/CF_SEP/Unincorporated Territories","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"JXhESRyhUbArTc5h","name":"Sanctean Primarchy","content":"<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong>Official Name: </strong></span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\">Il Primarchio del Arx Sanctea (The Primarchy of Arx Sanctea)</span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong>Capital: </strong></span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\">Sanctea (Formerly named Arcis Aurum)</span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.25in;text-indent:-.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong>Head of State: </strong></span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\">His Holiness, Primarch Salvatore IX, Dean of the College of Cardinals, Abbot of the Justicar Order of St. Callisto, Voice Plenipotent of Deum Ruling.</span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.25in;text-indent:-.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong>Primary Inhabitants: </strong></span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\">Humans</span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.25in;text-indent:-.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong>Currency:</strong></span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"> Florin (gp), piastra (sp), grana (cp)</span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong> </strong></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\">Sanctea is a theocracy governed by priests of Deus Ruling, the god of law, order, and civilization. The country broke away from the Novan Imperium eight centuries ago, due to religious strife fueled by an unorthodox interpretation of Deus Ruling’s holy text, <em>il Libro del Legge</em>. </span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"> </span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"font-size:14.0pt\">History</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\">Religion held a great deal of significance in the ancient Auran empire: as humanity lacked large numbers of sorcerers or knowledge of wizardry, the most commonly-seen magic in Arcis Aurum was that of empowered priests, and even they were considerably rarer than they are today. The Auran kings and queens held an assortment of ceremonial positions in various temples and churches, and were revered as living saints or even demigods in certain unorthodox faiths.</span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\">On the other hand, after the Collapse, the early Emperors of the Novan Imperium—the would-be successors to the Auran Empire—did not care to share power with priests or temples: they intended to rebuild the Empire in their image, and distrusted the idea of their citizens and soldiers having split loyalties. As a result the early Emperors stamped out any temples that they could not control and use in their campaigns of re-conquest. Those which remained (largely dedicated to militant or law-abiding deities, such as Deum Militant, Deum Valiant, or Deum Ruling) were subordinated to the Imperial government.</span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\">The temples of Deum Ruling were the most content with this arrangement: as followers of the god of law, order, and civilization, they were more than willing to support the Novan Imperium as it became a beacon of civilization in the darkness of the Collapse. The emperors employed the empowered priests of Deum Ruling as arbiters and investigators among their Quaestors—agents who rooted out corruption and conspiracies in the Novan government—while the temples’ rank and file preached obedience to authority.</span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\">This state of affairs persisted through the reigns of the first two emperors, until Gaius III became set upon reclaiming Arcis Aurum itself. His attempt failed catastrophically, but not before certain Quaestors were sent into the orc-inhabited ruins of the once-great city. One of these, a crusader of Deum Ruling by the name of Quintus Palfuria, returned with an ancient text, which he claimed to be the original, divinely-inspired copy of <em>il Libro del Legge,</em> or <em>Book of Laws</em>, recovered from the ruins of the Lexeum, the oldest and greatest of his god’s temples.</span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\">Eschewing all assistance from the other members of his order, Quintus undertook the laborious process of translating the holy book from the ancient tongue in which it was written, a process which took years. When he unveiled his finished translation, it sparked riots, as his translation called for the faithful to obey Deum Ruling’s priests over all other authorities—and to remove nonbelievers from authority, by the sword if necessary.</span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\">Not all of Deum Ruling’s faithful followed this call—in fact, many of the god’s priests denounced Quintus Palfuria as an incompetent or a self-serving fraud, as his translation matched no previous edition of the <em>Book of Laws</em>. Nonetheless, his message attracted enough followers to form an insurrection which further weakened the Novan Imperium in the aftermath of Gaius III’s disastrous reign. The newly-anointed Empress Juliana was willing neither to submit to Palfuria’s demands, nor to make a martyr of him: instead, she offered a compromise: Palfuria and his followers were exiled from the central provinces of the Imperium, but would be permitted to preach and to govern themselves (following Novan standards) in the dangerous eastern provinces where orcs still raided on a regular basis. No doubt Juliana hoped that this would make her citizens less eager to join Palfuria, but instead, they embraced it. Palfuria led his followers to settle tracts of land on the eastern border, from which they pushed outwards, conquering additional territory back from the orcs. Although they nominally claimed it for the glory of the Novan Imperium, it rapidly became apparent that this land truly belonged to Palfuria’s crusade: between additional converts from the Imperium, and foreign pilgrims who viewed this as Deum Ruling’s promised land, the newly-conquered provinces became populated almost exclusively by the god’s devoted followers.</span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\">Three centuries after the exile, the Palfurian Crusade succeeded in reclaiming Arcis Aurum itself, much to the chagrin of the Novan Imperium. They lavishly restored the ancient temples to Deum Ruling, while tearing down the city’s other temples in their process of rebuilding—and at this point, with the ancient seat of humanity safely in their grasp, the Crusade finally declared its independence from the Imperium, declaring themselves the Sanctean Primarchy and renaming the ancient city as Arx Sanctea.</span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\">The Sancteans have since had several conflicts with the Novan Imperium, culminating in an all-out war during the Wars of Smoke and Steel. Though the Novan Legions were able to conquer parts of the Primarchy in each conflict, they found themselves unable to win the hearts and minds of the inhabitants: despite strict curfews and efforts to disarm the civilian populace, Novan patrols found themselves ambushed by mobs on a regular basis, while in the Imperium, sympathizers committed acts of sabotage and terrorism until it became politically unviable to continue the occupation. The two countries remain in an uneasy peace, with Novan Quaestors and Sanctean zealots regularly coming into conflict with each other at the border.</span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"> </span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"font-size:14.0pt\">Politics</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\">When the Primarchy gained independence, they structured their government to incorporate the many religious orders that had joined or formed under the banner of the Palfurian Crusade: each order was granted a piece of land, in which their ordained priests would enforce the laws of Deum Ruling. Each of these orders also participates in the election of the Primarch, who is the sole priest permitted to read the original <em>Book of Laws.</em></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\">Although all of the orders represented in the Primarchy have accepted Palfuria’s translation of the <em>Book of Laws</em>, there is still some variation in how they interpret it. Some of these disagreements are minor: in some parts of Sanctea, it is forbidden to work from sunrise to sundown on holy days, while in others, it is forbidden from one sunrise to the next. Other disagreements are more problematic: certain hardline orders interpret the command to remove nonbelievers from authority as requiring all figures of authority to be ordained priests—and as such, the priests of this order are reluctant to obey the instructions of un-priestly authorities such as mayors or constables in the domains of less restrictive orders.</span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\">This conflict has only gotten worse as the years pass and new interpretations of the <em>Book of Laws</em> are proposed, to the point that recent Primarchs have instituted an Inquisition to identify heretical interpretations among the many orders. The Inquisition has so far been restricted to policing the clergy, but there are rumors that the High Inquisitor now seeks to be granted authority over the average citizens of the Primarchy. Considering the zeal of the Inquisition, and the tortures that they often put suspected heretics to, many citizens live in fear of this authority being granted.</span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"> </span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"font-size:14.0pt\">Society</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\">The Primarchy is located in what were once the heartlands of Arcis Aurum. These lands are incredibly fertile, thanks to extensive flood plains and river deltas, and so much of the Primarchy is agrarian. The various religious orders making up the Primarchy own most of the country’s farmland, however; they employ farmers to work the land, but keep a large share of the crop for themselves—both to feed the priesthood, and to fund their charitable and other activities.</span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\">Between the charity of various orders of the priesthood, and the presence of many empowered priests with healing magic, even the poorest citizen has a high standard of living compared to other nations: poverty is almost unheard-of, and it is rare that anyone dies of disease or any but the most sudden and violent of accidents. However, this is all dependent upon being a faithful worshipper of Deum Ruling: suspicions of apostasy, blasphemy, or heresy can quickly lead to the loss of one’s home, livelihood, or worse. Many of the more fundamentalist and militant orders practice conscription or forced religious re-education within their territories, and others are quick to enforce harsh penalties for perceived violations of Deum Ruling’s laws. As the only path to high positions of power is to join the clergy, and strictly follow one of the established interpretations of the <em>Book of Laws</em>, there are few opportunities for free-thinkers or the less-devout to appeal to higher authorities or enact change.</span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\">Additionally, it is also difficult for citizens to leave Sanctea. Many orders require emigrants to pay steep tithes before leaving, and the great powers are often reluctant to accept Sanctean immigrants, as the Primarchy is known for its use of partisan fighters to spread dissent and conflict. Many who leave Sanctea do so by fleeing in the night, and wind up in lawless places like the Horselands or the Unclaimed Reaches.</span></p>\n<p><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman',serif;mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA\"> </span></span></p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"hsFJxrWN4M5Ezw3L":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.aetrimonde_v0_8_x.aetrimonde-setting.JXhESRyhUbArTc5h"},"cf":{"id":"temp_i4cc68g5ub","path":"The World of Aetrimonde#/CF_SEP/Major Polities","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"KghKxYOF1oObtapx","name":"Victovy-Waystone Buffer Zone","content":"<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">As part of the peace treaty which ended the war between Victovy and Waystone, both nations agreed not to interfere with the territories abandoned by Victovy in their retreat, leaving them independent and neutral. This left a stretch of city-states and small nations between the two former enemies, ensuring that Victovy and Waystone did not have to share a border. Of course, while both nations have held to the letter of their agreement, they both wish to have allies in the buffer zone should war break out once again. Accordingly, the two nations are now engaged in a subtler conflict, competing for the allegiance of the buffer states using diplomacy, espionage, and other intrigues.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">The city of Sagrenna hosts embassies from both Victovy and Waystone, as well as many of the other city-states in the Buffer Zone. As such, it is a hotbed of intrigue, as agents of the two great powers engage in diplomacy, espionage, blackmail, intrigue, and other such plots to advance their positions in the supposedly neutral region. At the same time, the city-states attempt to play both sides against each other, sometimes to maintain the status quo and sometimes to gain an advantage over their local rivals. As such, there are a multitude of prospective employers for adventurers willing to become entangled in the \"great game,\" as many of the local power brokers call it.</span></span></p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":2,"hsFJxrWN4M5Ezw3L":3,"lh2XdhvmO8rwUMvb":2},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.aetrimonde_v0_8_x.aetrimonde-setting.KghKxYOF1oObtapx"},"cf":{"id":"temp_w4yki4y5ebj","path":"The World of Aetrimonde#/CF_SEP/Minor Polities","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"OjgSPYXfNurHpqwK","name":"The Restless Sea","content":"<p>The Restless Sea is bordered to the west by the continent of Kaern and to the north and south by island chains that blunt the worst of Aetrimonde's maritime storms. It is not a safe ocean to sail, but it is certainly safer than most. Here, ships are able to sail away from the coast without fear of being sunk by the first storm to hit them, and there are many trade routes crossing the middle of the Sea carrying such exotic goods as serpent oil from Butcher's Bay, machinery from the Novan Imperium, and sanctified incense and unguents from the Sanctean Primarchy. </p>\n<p>The danger of sailing the Restless Sea is piracy. In the south, corsairs sail with impunity from Nintar and the other pirate havens of the Cape of Corsairs, but there are also pirate nests in the Serpent Isles, and privateers from the Imperium and the Primarchy who are commissioned to attack any vessel not flying under a neutral flag. Even in these waters, most merchant ships fly the flag of Waystone, as the Royal Navy's piracy-suppression patrols have a long arm and a fearsome reputation.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"txsdYu7V4ixj4DHp":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_aixisdz1brv","path":"The World of Aetrimonde#/CF_SEP/Bodies of Water","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"OwoI5IymKoOKhJGR","name":"The Serpent Isles","content":"<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Although most of Aetrimonde’s sea monsters dwell within deep waters far from shore, a few species seem to prefer shallower waters. Sea serpents, in particular, congregate around the Serpent Isles named for them. The serpents are a danger to fishermen and maritime trade alike, and in recent years trading companies from Victovy have placed a bounty on the monsters, hoping that by thinning their numbers they might make their northern sea routes more competitive with the southern shipping route dominated by Waystone. Serpent-hunting has turned into a veritable industry in the Serpent Isles, and has made a serious dent in the beats’ population. However, a number of naturalists have begun to issue warnings about the serpent hunts, noting that as the serpent population declines, sightings of larger kraken and leviathans are on the rise…</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\">There are few cities of note in the Isles themselves, but the mainland port of Butchers' Bay, a rough and rowdy city with an everpresent aroma of fish guts, is the home port to most of the serpent-hunters. Hunting vessels bring many of their catches into the harbor to be processed for meat, oil, and valuable alchemical products. The alchemical substances find their way to markets around the continent, while much of the oil is burned for light in the city. Serpent meat, formerly cheap and plentiful around Butchers' Bay, has become a delicacy elsewhere, and much of it is now processed, canned, and shipped out by a handful of rich merchants.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":2,"hsFJxrWN4M5Ezw3L":3,"lh2XdhvmO8rwUMvb":2},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.aetrimonde_v0_8_x.aetrimonde-setting.OwoI5IymKoOKhJGR"},"cf":{"id":"temp_jtqi9qh2rjq","path":"The World of Aetrimonde#/CF_SEP/Unincorporated Territories","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"T2hySB0rtKRnArbe","name":"The Continent of Kaern","content":"<p>Kaern contains seven nations of significance (the \"major polities\") as well as an assortment of minor nations, city-states, and unincorporated regions without an overarching government. All are successors to an earlier age of civilization, which was destroyed more than a thousand years ago in an event called the Collapse brought on by short-sighted wars. These successor-states have rebuilt and, for the most part, are more advanced--socially, scientifically, technologically, and magically--than their predecessors, but have developed along different paths and still have not recovered some of the secrets lost in the Collapse.</p>\n<p>Nor are modern nations immune to the follies of their predecessors: another series of wars beginning just over two centuries ago threatened to cause another Collapse, and indeed the final days of these wars saw the deployment of superweapons that might have made Kaern uninhabitable had they seen wider use. Ultimately, the terror caused by these weapons forced the warring nations to seek peace, and for the last 87 years, an uneasy armistice has held sway over Kaern.</p>\n<p>The armistice has not eliminated the major polities' grievances against each other: rather, it has moved their conflicts into new arenas. Institutions built to preserve the armistice have thus far prevented further armed conflict, aside from a few proxy wars fought by minor polities on behalf of their patrons. Conflicts are now fought using diplomacy, espionage, economics and culture--and where all else fails, the services of discreet and deniable adventurers.</p>\n<p>The unincorporated territories of Kaern still hold secrets from the previous civilizations, not to mention new secrets belonging to scholars and magicians who left civilization behind to pursue their esoteric studies. These untamed lands are also home to powerful monsters: dragons and vampires are fond of making their lairs away from population centers, and the magicians who traffic with demons and otherworldly spirits do so far from the authorities who would hunt them down for it. Expeditions into the wilds, to seek the relics of history or slay troublesome monsters, can be lucrative for a well-prepared band of adventurers...if they return alive.</p>\n<p>Little is known of the world outside of Kaern and its outlying islands: to the north of Kaern is a vast sheet of ice, some parts of which have been explored, but on all other sides, the continent is surrounded by deep sea. Aetrimonde's ocean is exceedingly dangerous for a combination of reasons:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Aetrimonde's three moons act upon each other in a complex but apparently stable orbital system, leading to highly unpredictable tides and currents. Even in familiar waters, ships caught by a surprise current can easily be driven aground or lost at sea.</li>\n<li>Similarly erratic weather patterns form in the seas around Kaern, as the unpredictable currents can bring concentrations of warm water near shore with little warning. Powerful storms frequently, but irregularly, blow in from the west, posing a further risk to ships outside of secure anchorages.</li>\n<li>Finally, Aetrimonde's seas are home to several varieties of \"sea monster,\" from shallows-dwelling serpents large enough to coil around an entire ship, to even larger kraken and leviathan inhabiting deeper parts of  the ocean.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Between these hazards, few ships that stray far from shore and safe harbors ever return. Every few decades, a determined voyager, or a cargo ship blown far off-course, returns with news of a distant new island and sometimes a previously-uncontacted tribe, but no explorer has ever returned from discovering a continent of similar size to Kaern. So far as the people of Kaern know, they are alone on Aetrimonde, although they can tell from astronomy and mathematics that their world must be far larger than the area they know...</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"txsdYu7V4ixj4DHp":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_as0g13ftc5q","path":"The World of Aetrimonde","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"UariLqRvmSrGTJ4g","name":"The Frozen Isles","content":"<p>To the north of Kaern lie the Frozen Isles, which are mostly barren spits of rock emerging from a sea that is frigid in summer, and packed with sea-ice in winter. Although this northern passage offers a shorter voyage between the eastern and western coasts of Kaern, it is virtually unnavigable for almost half of the year.</p>\n<p>Even when the sea-ice is less of an issue in summer, the Frozen Isles are home to their own brand of corsairs and pirates, less numerous and organized than their counterparts on the Cape of Corsairs, and yet far more dangerous. There is significant overlap between the local pirates and the cults that make their lairs in these barren islands: many a pirate crew contains diablerists, necromancers, or mindslavers eager to raid merchant ships and coastal villages for supplies and captives. To make matters worse, Waystone's piracy-suppression patrols seldom sail these waters, as Victovy only rarely grants passage to its rival's ships, and Victovy's own navy is not nearly as effective.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"txsdYu7V4ixj4DHp":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_aixisdz1brv","path":"The World of Aetrimonde#/CF_SEP/Bodies of Water","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"UyFOGhfAOSwLMuf8","name":"The Autonomous Clans","content":"<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">At the western edge of the Dwarven Federation is a region claimed by the so-called “Autonomous Clans,” whose relationship with the Federation is unclear, even to the dwarves themselves. Although they honor dwarven laws, the Autonomous Clans have no representation on the council of Thanes, and make their own treaties with foreign powers independently of the rest of the Federation. Additionally, the culture within the Autonomous Clans is very different from mainstream dwarven culture: here, the dwarves honor their ancestors by building and innovating on their inventions, rather than by maintaining their ancestors’ work exactly as it was. Many of the Autonomous Clans develop weapons—including sophisticated firearms, alchemical explosives, and powerful enchantments—for sale to the highest bidder, and have much closer relations with outsiders than the rest of the dwarves. There is even a growing independence movement which seeks to split entirely from the Dwarven Federation, which they view and pointlessly stuck in the past—tensions between this movement and the traditionalists in the Federation are high, but have not yet spilled over into violence.</span></span></p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":2,"hsFJxrWN4M5Ezw3L":3,"lh2XdhvmO8rwUMvb":2},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.aetrimonde_v0_8_x.aetrimonde-setting.UyFOGhfAOSwLMuf8"},"cf":{"id":"temp_w4yki4y5ebj","path":"The World of Aetrimonde#/CF_SEP/Minor Polities","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"dgQa5qi9I5pY7Mv6","name":"Tir Coetir","content":"<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Official Name: </span></strong></span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Tir Coetir y Corachod (The Woodland Realm of the Elves)</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Capital: </span></strong></span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">The Itinerant Court</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.25in;text-indent:-.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Head of State: </span></strong></span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Queen Aemalla the Huntress, Lady of the Deep Woods, Beloved of Spirits, Bearer of the Elder Crown and the Rowan Rod.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.25in;text-indent:-.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Primary Inhabitants: </span></strong></span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Elves</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.25in;text-indent:-.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Currency:</span></strong></span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\"> Ceiniog (gp), dymey (sp), firdlyc (cp). Used mainly for transactions with foreigners: barter is far more common domestically.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\"> </span></strong></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Tir Coetir is home to the elves who reject the ancient traditions of Caras Seidharen. It is a primeval forest, home to small, close-packed villages, and no settlements at all which are larger than a mid-sized town: even the Queen of Tir Coetir rules from a travelling court, which resides in various towns for a few weeks at a time, moving on at the Queen’s whim. Outside of a few strongholds where the laws are well-enforced, it can be an unforgiving place to outsiders: many a traveler has gone missing in the deep woods, taken by bandits, nature spirits, or even druidic cults.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"font-size:16.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt\"> </span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:11.0pt\">History</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">In the Age of Glory, the ancient elves claimed the densely-forested lands in the northeastern parts of the continent. They were the first race to develop sorcery, and their civilization, Caras Seidharen, rose to great heights based on their command of magic. However, the primacy of magic naturally caused the elves to be ruled by sorcerers: by the Age of Tyrants, a dynasty of despotic sorcerer-kings ruled the elves, and engaged in slavery, blood sports and a variety of dark magics to maintain their rule.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">It was these sorcerer-kings who kicked off the Collapse when they goaded the orcs into attacking their rivals in Arcis Aurum. Having overrun the human kingdom, the orcs proceeded to rampage onward into Caras Seidharen. When they realized the seriousness of their predicament, the ruling class vanished into the realm of Faerie with their most loyal retainers, abandoning the bulk of the elven people.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">The elves who survived the Collapse—mostly those who fled to distant outposts in the west—fell into two camps: <span style=\"mso-spacerun:yes\"> </span>those who rejected arcane magic and the other legacies of Caras Seidharen retreated into the depths of the Great Forest of Tir Coetir, a primeval wilderness which concealed them from the prying eyes of destructive outsiders.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">However, without the magic that had supported Caras Seidharen, these wood elves found themselves struggling to feed themselves. They spent decades attempting to farm on the outskirts of the forest, supplementing their food supply by hunting, foraging, and occasionally breaking down and using arcane magic. These uses of magic inevitably led to mobs and purges by hardline anti-arcanist factions, until a compromise was reached: rather than abandon magic entirely, the wood elves turned to other, older magics. They sought out and appeased spirits of nature, using them to encourage the growth of crops and hunt wild animals through the depths of the forest. </span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">This use of primal magics changed the wood elves: once sophisticated urbanites like their brethren the high elves, over a handful of generations they embraced their simpler existence, scattering to tiny woodland villages and all but abandoning the small city that they had built at the heart of the forest. They mostly abandoned their traditional religions, with most beginning to worship the spirits that brought them sustenance, and they maintained their isolation by ruthlessly killing any outsiders who ventured too close to their borders without permission—and such permission was rarely granted. For the rare occasions when they had to communicate or negotiate with outsiders, the wood elves chose to crown a king, who would speak for them but not rule them. After much discussion, they settled on Ceredwyn the Protector, a warrior who had shepherded many refugees safely to their new home. King Ceredwyn leveraged his renown to supplement his formal power and was able to mold the culture of his new nation, but his descendants did not hold the same degree of respect. Over the years the royals were relegated to figureheads, with the true power in Tir Coetir belonging to various local lords and druidic cults.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">The wood elves did not face any challenge to their isolationism for centuries, until the beginning of the Wars of Smoke and Steel. While the major powers fought each other, the conflicts of the Petty Kingdoms to the south began to spill over into the forest of Tir Coetir, which the warring warlords believed to be largely uninhabited. At first, the wood elves remained content to let the humans kill each other within their territory (and then mop up the survivors, if necessary), but it soon became apparent that the intruders had no intention of leaving their forest once they had won. The scattered elven villages were initially unable to oppose this encroachment, and were forced to abandon their holdings and flee further into the forest. </span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">As news of the human incursions spread through the forest realm, warlike elves from throughout Tir Coetir gathered to oppose them, although their efforts only slowed the humans’ advance into the forest. However, the wood elves’ current king, Melwyr the Vanquisher, greatly savored his hunts—and, it was rumored, secretly participated in bloody druidic rituals. He came to view this human invasion as merely a new kind of hunt, and he began to lead vicious hit-and-run attacks which terrorized the human settlers. Faced with a forest which seemed to conceal an archer or a bloody-handed druid behind every tree, the humans eventually fled the forest.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">After this victory, Melwyr enjoyed great acclaim from his subjects, and was able to reclaim some of the respect and glory that King Ceredwyn once held. At the same time, he came to recognize that the wood elves could no longer afford to ignore the outside world entirely. At the conclusion of the Wars of Smoke and Steel, Melwyr unexpectedly began to send ambassadors to the other major powers, and in the end he permitted small numbers of merchants to enter into the forest. Trade with the outside world brought greater prosperity to the wood elves—but Melwyr also ensured that the merchants saw the skill of his archers and the magic of his druids, and carried the tales to any would-be invaders.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\"> </span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"font-size:14.0pt\">Politics</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Much of the power in Tir Coetir still lies in the many small villages scattered throughout the forest. Thanks to Melwyr’s wartime leadership, his daughter Aemalla can call upon her subjects to provide levies of archers or druidic magic for the defense of the woodland realm, but she has little control over the laws and customs of individual villages, which are still ruled by an assortment of hereditary nobles, village councils, and druidic priests. </span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">More importantly, Aemalla seldom feels the need to exercise her power: she grew up in a time when Tir Coetir was peaceful and prosperous, thanks to renewed trade, and as long as she has access to the luxuries of the outside world—wine, exotic spices and rich textiles, even some arcane magical conveniences, despite the wood elves’ general dislike for them—she is content to spend her days hunting and sporting throughout the woodland realm, leaving actual rulership to local authorities.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">This lax policy has allowed some especially remote parts of Tir Coetir to effectively ignore Melwyr’s decrees: these remote settlements no longer contribute soldiers to the defense of the realm, or permit outsiders to pass through peacefully. They have all but officially declared their independence from Aemalla’s rule, and she seems perfectly content to let them. In these unruly parts of Tir Coetir, many of the local lords have grown power-mad, abducting travelers to hunt for sport, or to sacrifice to their bloodthirsty patron spirits.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"font-size:14.0pt\">Society</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">The wood elves of Tir Coetir live close to nature; even in larger towns, the buildings are built around, or even into, the living trees of the forest. Many wood elves, including the queen herself, are nomadic and travel from village to village as whim or necessity takes them.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Even the non-nomadic wood elves live relatively simple lives, compared to the other great powers. This is partly by choice—the culture fostered by Ceredwyn the Protector places little value on material objects—but it is also because the wood elves have little of value to begin with. Their forest contains very little in the way of mineral resources, and those only in the north, at the foothills of the Ironspine mountains. Agriculture is likewise difficult in the deep forest, and so the only goods of value that the elves have are rare woods from the depths of the forest, unusual botanical extracts, and the skins and furs they gain from hunting. There are few merchants among the elves—craftsmen and gatherers tend to simply sell their own products—but a growing number of local lords have begun enriching themselves by taxing trade with foreign merchants.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Instead of wealth and lavish lifestyles, the elves of Tir Coetir treasure song and laughter. While they are not exactly communal, their communities are tight-knit and host regular festivals and celebrations with plentiful food, music, dancing, and poetry.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">The druids of Tir Coetir are almost a separate people, however. Spirits are affected by mortal perceptions of them, and so many of the spirits in Tir Coetir—where the elves view them as generous providers—have grown tame and cooperative. But in the deep parts of the forest, there are spirits which prey upon mortals, reveling in their fear and growing ever more terrible from it. It falls to the druids to contain these spirits: they construct wards to keep dangerous spirits away from villages, and drive them back when they grow too bold…and when all else fails, appease them with the appropriate sacrifices. The burden of combating these dark spirits is a heavy one, and the druids are both respected and shunned, for though their task is important, it is also unsavory, reminding the wood elves of the price they must pay for isolation.</span></span></p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"hsFJxrWN4M5Ezw3L":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.aetrimonde_v0_8_x.aetrimonde-setting.dgQa5qi9I5pY7Mv6"},"cf":{"id":"temp_i4cc68g5ub","path":"The World of Aetrimonde#/CF_SEP/Major Polities","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"dqRxyYPADk7yTZIt","name":"The Vale of Glories","content":"<p>Nestled between two branches of the Ironspine Mountains is the Vale of Glories, a valley containing the ruins of both Konigstrond and Caras Seidharen, ancient empires of the dwarves and Elves. While many of the riches and ancient artifacts of these empires were looted by the orcs who overthrew them, some still hope that the lost secrets of their ancestors remain to be found. The dwarves, in particular, desire to reclaim the avalanche-buried ruins of Konigstrond, where they hope to find some clue to how their ancestors worked admantine. The elves, for their part, remain tight-lipped about what they hope to find in the toppled spires of Caras Elvaren, but they quietly acquire many pieces of magical wreckage that adventurers bring back from expeditions into the ruins.</p>\n<p>While factions among the dwarves and elves would zealously like to reclaim their people's former territory, they are kept from doing so by one major complication: the Vale is heavily populated by savage orcs. These are not the civilized descendents of the horde that overthrew the ancient empires, nor the shamanic pacifists that remained in the orc homelands; they are the successors to the bloodthirsty conquerors of old, and their numbers have been swelled by fifty generations of violent outcasts exiled from Urku. The dwarves face constant border skirmishes with the horde, and would be hard-pressed to actually push into the Vale. The elves, who lack the dwarves' foothold in the mountains, would find it an even more daunting task. For the foreseeable future, the Vale is likely to remain in orc hands.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"txsdYu7V4ixj4DHp":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_jtqi9qh2rjq","path":"The World of Aetrimonde#/CF_SEP/Unincorporated Territories","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"gqZHWFiG7klMyEhS","name":"Timeline","content":"<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt\">The Age of Myth: Before c. 2500 B.A. (Before Armistice)</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\">Little is known of the time before the rise of the first great empires. Scholars have attempted to draw conclusions from cave paintings, carvings in ancient ruins, and the work of earlier scholars addressing the same question, but there are no easy conclusions: myths and legends speak of gods and angels walking among mortals, titans which shaped the world, and terrible beasts which menaced early mortals. </span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"> </span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt\">The Age of Glory: c. 2500 – 1200 B.A.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\">This age began with the founding of Gjalerbron, the first, great, kingdom of the dwarves. It was shortly followed by Arcis Aurum, Caras Seidharen, and Gobol Karn</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\">Gjalerbron was built upon the masterful craftsmanship of the dwarves and their mastery of mithril, adamantine, and the runes of power.</span></li>\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\">Arcis Aurum was built upon sheer numbers and brute force: the teeming masses of humanity built temples and monuments larger even than the dwarves’, though not so finely wrought or sturdy.</span></li>\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\">Caras Seidharen was built upon the sorcery of powerful bloodlines among the elves, and was ruled by dynasties of sorcerer-kings capable of unparalleled feats of magic.</span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:9.0pt;font-family:Symbol;mso-fareast-font-family:Symbol;mso-bidi-font-family:Symbol\"><span style=\"font-variant-numeric:normal;font-variant-east-asian:normal;font-stretch:normal;font-size:7pt;line-height:normal;font-family:'Times New Roman'\"> </span></span></span></li>\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\">Gobol Karn was built using slavery on a massive scale, augmented using goblin alchemy to control and alter its slaves and beasts of burden. It was short-lived, collapsing under a combination of inbreeding, decadence, and slave uprisings.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\">The Age of Glory saw the invention of wizardry and enchantment, and the first expeditions onto other planes of existence.</span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoListParagraph\" style=\"margin-left:0in;mso-add-space:auto\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"> </span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt\">The Collapse: 1200 – 1180 B.A.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\">The fall of the three remaining great empires was kicked off by a war between Arcis Aurum and Caras Seidharen, when humanity’s continual expansion led them to settle lands claimed by the elves, displacing the inhabitants. The Sidhe, rulers of Caras Seidharen, expected an easy victory, but discovered that humanity possessed an enormous advantage in numbers. To tip the scales, they enticed the reclusive orcs to make war upon Arcis Aurum as well—only to lose control of the orcs, who promptly overran Arcis Aurum and Caras Seidharen entirely. The dwarves eventually defeated the orc horde in a pyrrhic victory that shattered Gjalerbron as well.</span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"> </span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt\">The Interregnum: 1180 – 115 B.A.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\">After the Collapse, civilization rebuilt, leading to the rise of numerous nations, including seven major polities:</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\">Caras Elvaren, the near-anarchistic but magically poten nation of the high elves,</span></li>\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\">The Dwarven Federation, a collection of dwarven clans who cling to the remnants of ancient Gjalerbron.</span></li>\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\">The Novan Imperium, a highly industrialized but bureaucratic nation which claims to be the rightful successor to Arcis Aurum.</span></li>\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\">Sanctea, a theocracy dedicated to the god of law and civilization, and another would-be successor to Arcis Aurum.</span></li>\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\">Tir Coetir, isolationist and xenophobic nation of the wood elves.</span></li>\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\">Victovy, a dictatorship which is torn between aggressive imperialism and cultural hegemony.</span></li>\n<li class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\">Waystone, a small but influential nation of traders and diplomats.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\">This era saw further developments in alchemy and engineering, leading to firearms, steam engines, and the industrial revolution. Coupled with advances in magical theory, this also led to the first devices which combined magic and technology, such as thinking engines and steam-powered death rays.</span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"> </span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt\">The Wars of Smoke and Steel: 115 – 3 B.A.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\">The expanding major polities fought a series of increasingly-destructive wars using their arsenals of technological and magical weapons, culminating in a brief exchange of superweapons that wiped several cities out of existence. This unprecedented devastation shocked the belligerents into accepting an armistice proposed by Caras Elvaren, who had remained neutral throughout most of the conflict.</span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"> </span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt\">The Modern Age: 3 B.A. – 87 P.A. (Post-Armistice)</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\">It took three years, but the great powers were successful in winding down their wars and establishing what seems to be a lasting peace. A grand international council has been established in the city of Waystone, for the purpose of avoiding another destructive war. Is has thus far been successful in preventing another world-ending war, although it has not kept the major polities from bickering and scheming against each other, or even engaging in proxy wars through their allies in the minor polities.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"txsdYu7V4ixj4DHp":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_as0g13ftc5q","path":"The World of Aetrimonde","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"jN6y3Q37Jl7lzqnZ","name":"The Salvage Coast","content":"<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">The coastline west of Waystone was once a hotbed of piracy to rival the Cape of Corsairs: the coast here is battered by frequent, unpredictable storms off of the Storm-Wracked Sea, and the rocky coastline contains many hidden coves suitable for pirate dens. Thanks to Waystone’s Royal Navy, which extended its piracy-suppression patrols down the western coast, those pirate dens have been turned into mere fishing villages. The locals remain no less opportunistic, however: ships often run aground in unforeseen storms, and word of a shipwreck is enough to bring villagers rushing from their homes to salvage what they can from the wreck—even as the storm still rages. Shipwrecked mariners would be well-advised to surrender their cargoes and accept the villagers’ offer of a hot meal and warm blankets, for the locals still have something of a piratical streak—sailors trying to hold onto their cargo are often “lost to the waves” in suspicious circumstances.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\">The more respectable ports along the Salvage Coast are not centers of trade or industry, as the people of the Salvage Coast are largely fishermen and farmers. Instead, ports like Froetegard, Westerhaven and Zuidpoort grew up as safe anchorages for ships to flee to ahead of an incoming storm, and they still make a lucrative profit by charging exorbitant harbor fees to ships suprised by foul weather. Though they may grumble, merchant captains generally choose to pay these fees rather than risk running aground or striking a reef in one of the untimely storms common to the area.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":2,"hsFJxrWN4M5Ezw3L":3,"lh2XdhvmO8rwUMvb":2},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.aetrimonde_v0_8_x.aetrimonde-setting.jN6y3Q37Jl7lzqnZ"},"cf":{"id":"temp_w4yki4y5ebj","path":"The World of Aetrimonde#/CF_SEP/Minor Polities","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"lNlQoMw5KAgw4Wo0","name":"The Horselands","content":"<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Northeast of Sanctea, there lies a great plain, an ocean of grass as far as the eye can see. The land is only passably fertile, especially compared to the river valleys of Sanctea, and so there has never been any sustained effort to claim it—especially considering the current inhabitants, who are warlike tribes of nomadic raiders. Although mostly human, there are orcs mixed in among them: descendants of the horde which destroyed Arcis Aurum or outcasts from the frozen north. The tribes constantly raid each other and their neighbors, and attempts to settle the plains inevitably end beneath the hooves of an onrushing horde.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">The sole city of the Horselands is Urtuk Pardu, inasmuch as it can actually be called a city. Located at the fork of a major river, the \"city\" is in reality a gigantic temporary encampment, which shifts, grows, and shrinks depending on how many of the nomads have come to trade, carouse, seal pacts, request the wisdom of elders, or seek mercenary employment. By a longstanding tradition of sacred hospitality, feuds between clans camped at Urtuk Pardu must be set aside until three days after the clan departs, but that does not make the city peaceful: the nights are punctuated with drunken brawls, fights over the spoils of war, quarrels over the hand of a lover, and many other sources of violence, many of which are pretexts for feuding clans to fight each other without breaking the tradition of hospitality. Outsiders are even less protected by the tradition of hospitality, as few of the clans would bother to avenge injuries done to an interloper sticking their nose where they don't belong (which is how most of them view visitors from the \"civilized\" west).</span></span></p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":2,"hsFJxrWN4M5Ezw3L":3,"lh2XdhvmO8rwUMvb":2},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.aetrimonde_v0_8_x.aetrimonde-setting.lNlQoMw5KAgw4Wo0"},"cf":{"id":"temp_jtqi9qh2rjq","path":"The World of Aetrimonde#/CF_SEP/Unincorporated Territories","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"piG0dgl04Pxz1RK3","name":"The Storm-Wracked Sea","content":"<p>The Storm-Wracked Sea is the most dangerous of the oceans surrounding Kaern. While Aetrimonde's oceans are all subject to erratic tides, currents, and weather, the storms blowing out of the west are by far the worst. It is simply suicidal for ships to stray far from shore into the Storm-Wracked Sea: the only way to safely sail these waters is to hug the coastline and make for a sheltered cove if the weather turns.</p>\n<p>Despite this, maritime trade is still common up and down this coast: safe harbors have been established all the way to the southern tip of the continent, and a ship with a competent captain can make the journey safely (if slowly) during most of the year. The most common cause of shipwrecks is haste, when a ship carrying a time-sensitive cargo tries to outsail a storm rather than anchor and ride it out.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"txsdYu7V4ixj4DHp":3},"flags":{"cf":{"id":"temp_aixisdz1brv","path":"The World of Aetrimonde#/CF_SEP/Bodies of Water","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"t7jiSAyaAsKbLdtK","name":"The Cape of Corsairs","content":"<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">South of the Novan Imperium lies the Cape of Corsairs, a peninsula home to all manner of pirates and privateers. They sail from free ports and hidden coves up and down the coast, preying on shipping from Waystone. The pirate kings of Nintar have turned piracy into a protection racket; for a nominal fee, they offer shipping companies free passage through their waters, and keep unaffiliated piracy to a minimum by raiding the hideouts of pirates who take too many of the ships that pay their fees. Of course, pirates being who they are, the pirate kings happily allow a little bit of \"poaching\" on their territory...so long as it happens quietly and they get a cut of the plunder.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Nintar itself is a nearly lawless city. The laws that do exist mostly deal with piratical concerns such as the fair distribution of plunder and rights to the ship's rum, but within the city limits, they are strictly enforced by an entity known as the Ancient Mariner, widely thought to be a spirit bound into service by the first pirate kings. Nonetheless, the Ancient Mariner enforces the Pirates' Code on all the inhabitants of Nintar, from the lowliest swabbie to the pirate kings themselves, and so Nintar's scoundrels and scallywags must walk a fine line in their scurrilous plots.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\">Another port of note is Ratline, located in the island chain that trails from the tip of the Cape. Mostly populated by black-hearted corsairs who fled Nintar one step ahead of the pirate kings (or the Ancient Mariner), it is somehow even more lawless than Nintar. While Nintar sometimes receives respectable visitors (such as merchants arriving to ransom their crew and cargo), any such innocents would be shot, robbed, and left for dead the instant they set foot on the Ratline pier.</p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":2,"hsFJxrWN4M5Ezw3L":3,"lh2XdhvmO8rwUMvb":2},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.aetrimonde_v0_8_x.aetrimonde-setting.t7jiSAyaAsKbLdtK"},"cf":{"id":"temp_w4yki4y5ebj","path":"The World of Aetrimonde#/CF_SEP/Minor Polities","color":"#000000"}}}
{"_id":"zrLpOtSLsUWptEui","name":"Victovy","content":"<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Official Name: </span></strong></span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Slavnaya Viktovaskaya Imperiya (The Glorious Victovan Empire)</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Capital: </span></strong></span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Fedotigrad</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.25in;text-indent:-.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Head of State: </span></strong></span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Galina Yelena Lidochka Andropova, Tsarina of all Victovy, Generalissima of the Grand Imperial Army and Subjugator of the Enemies of the Victs.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.25in;text-indent:-.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Primary Inhabitants: </span></strong></span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Humans, dwarves, orcs</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.25in;text-indent:-.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Currency:</span></strong></span><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\"> Rubles (gp), desyatki (sp), kopeks (cp).</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight:normal\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\"> </span></strong></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Victovy is an aggressively expansionistic nation, formerly a center of the arts and sciences but now ruled by a usurper backed by a military junta. It is a nation in turmoil, as the new empress and her conspirators crack down on dissent and build up their forces for the next war.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\"> </span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"font-size:14.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt\">History</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Although Arcis Aurum was the center of human civilization in the Age of Glory, humanity was spread throughout the world. In the northwest of the continent, numerous “barbarian” kingdoms flourished, far from the imperial rule of the Aurans. They warred frequently among themselves, and against outposts of the elves, dwarves, and orcs until the beginning of the Collapse.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">When the orcs overran Arcis Aurum and Caras Seidharen, refugees fled west before the oncoming hordes. The refugees who eventually reached what is now Victovy were a hardened bunch, having survived the horrors of the Collapse, but they brought with them knowledge of science, medicine, engineering, and even the rudiments of magic from the east. For a few short years, the northern kingdoms which took them in prospered.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Inevitably, this prosperity came to an end when the orcs followed behind the refugees. Having heard many tales of the orc invaders, most of the northern kingdoms had banded together, and were prepared to fight a desperate defense against the ravening horde—but instead, they faced innumerable bands of raiders which sought only to pillage and burn, and avoided the attempts to bring them to a decisive battle. This was all that was left of the horde, which had been broken by the last stand of the dwarf king.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">The uneasy alliance between the northern kingdoms held together for some years, but when it became obvious that the orcs were no longer a serious threat, the northern kings began to look to their own interests. Before the arrival of the orcs, they had often fought among themselves, and now, having raised larger armies to fend off an invasion which hadn’t materialized, they turned on each other.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">For two centuries, the northern kingdoms raided and conquered each other, and the orcs, and the occasional outsiders, and this state of affairs might have persisted if not for Georgei Androv, King of the Victs. Androv was well-known for ruthlessness, and was rumored to have assassinated his way to the throne; certainly his father, uncles, and older sister died untimely deaths, though they were never connected with Georgei. While leading his army against a neighboring rival, Androv discovered a band of orcs taking advantage of the chaos. As was common at the time, Androv called a ceasefire with his rival, and both armies marched upon the orcs—only for Androv to make common cause with the orcs instead, at which point he and the orcs fell upon and massacred his rival’s army.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Pleased with the success of this tactic, Androv swayed these orcs to his side, promising them plunder and tribute—as long as they refrained from killing too many serfs, and let him claim the lands for himself. This strategy worked alarmingly well, and Androv was cunning enough that he made efforts to integrate the orcs with his own forces. By the end of his lifetime, he had conquered nearly a third of the northern kingdoms, and had subverted several orc tribes into shock troops.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Georgei’s successors continued in his footsteps, unifying the northern kingdoms under Victish rule. Most of them were no less cunning than Georgei, and though they continued to expand their borders through conquest (and the threat of the orc regiments), they took pains to integrate their new vassals into their growing empire, taking the strengths of each conquered kingdom and making them their own, rather than imposing Victish culture on their subjects. The kings, and then the imperial Tsars, remained ruthlessly practical, and they had no qualms about adopting any culture, religion, invention, or dogma that they believed would strengthen Victovy, and thus, themselves. </span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Victovy continued to expand gradually by conquest, annexation, and colonization until the beginning of the Wars of Smoke and Steel, when they were stymied by a coalition led by the much smaller nation of Waystone. The Victovan military juggernaut stumbled as the coalition ignored its armies and instead struck at supply lines and industrial targets far behind the lines, and when the wars ended, Victovy had gained little territory while losing much of its industrial base to sabotage and surgical strikes.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">In the aftermath of the wars, Tsar Nikolaj the Learned adapted quickly to this new paradigm: as demonstrated by Waystone, the Victovan Empire could no longer count on expanding by force of arms alone. Taking inspiration from the diverse coalition that had defeated them, Nikolaj diverted funds from the military towards universities, with the intent of turning Victovy into a beacon of scientific progress. Almost as a side effect, this simultaneously revitalized the nation’s arts and culture, and the following years saw a resurgence in the traditional art, music, literature and theater of the empire’s many subject peoples.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Nikolaj’s attempt to make Victovy the cultural and scientific center of the known world was almost successful: during his reign, and that of his daughter Alexandra, the nation attracted intellectuals and artists from around the world, and the imperial capital of Fedotigrad rivaled Waystone as the most cosmopolitan city in the world. However, the defunding of the Victovan military left many influential officers dissatisfied. Nikolaj and Alexandra kept the army in check by purging officers who grew too outspoken, but unknown to them, a conspiracy began to grow in the upper ranks of the central command.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">The conspiracy found a receptive catspaw in Tsarina Alexandra’s younger daughter, Tsareva Galina, who had been sent to the army out of longstanding tradition. Then a mid-ranking officer of no particular talent, she eagerly joined the conspiracy when approached by one of her superior officers. Upon her mother’s death, Galina led the palace troops in a coup against her older brother Piotr. Denouncing the crown prince as unfit, due to a “weakness of the blood,” she ascended to the throne with the backing of the capitol’s garrison troops and promptly began issuing decrees for the rebuilding of the Victovan military.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in;tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\"> </span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"tab-stops:right 8.0in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"font-size:14.0pt\">Politics</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Victovy is, and always has been, a despotic dictatorship. The Tsar holds absolute power thanks to the backing of the army—though as seen recently, when a Tsar loses that backing, their days are numbered.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Victovy has no nobles and no hereditary aristocracy aside from the imperial family: the Tsar appoints governors for each province and offers fiefdoms to effective subordinates, but neither of these are hereditary. However, when Victovy began to industrialize, there arose the <em>boyars</em>, a class of merchants and industrialists who gained power through vast wealth. The Tsars tolerate the boyars, and even heed their counsel, because they are useful, even necessary, to keep the empire strong. The boyars control factories, mills, and laboratories which supply the Victovan military, and though they compete ruthlessly with each other for profit and the favor of the Tsar, they have enough self-preservation to present a united front whenever the Tsar appears eager to seize their fortunes.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Since Tsarina Galina’s ascent to the throne, she has had a second group of advisors in the nation’s High Command. These high-ranking officers control crucial regiments, and Galina’s reign is dependent on keeping their support—not that she has much difficulty doing so, for as a former officer herself, she shares many of their opinions. However, as she grows used to ruling, she is less and less beholden to the officers who backed her rise, and there are signs that her conspirators are losing their influence over her decisions. </span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Much of the High Command openly yearns for a new war to encourage patriotic fervor—and privately, they expect to grow rich from the spoils of war. The boyars, understanding that the war effort will likely be costly in the short term, oppose this aggression, and are dragging their feet when it comes to producing the war materiel demanded by the High Command. Very soon, tensions will come to a head.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\"> </span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"font-size:14.0pt\">Society</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">For much of Victovy’s history, the bulk of the population were serfs bound to the land and subject to the whims of whichever governor or friend of the Tsar had been appointed to rule them. To discourage peasant uprisings, serfs were barred from learning to read, owning property (and especially weapons), or travelling without special dispensations. Their sole path to prosperity was to enlist in the military, or be conscripted, and serve with distinction. </span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">In the years between the Wars of Smoke and Steel and Tsarina Galina’s coup, it became possible for serfs to escape their drudgery through education as scholars or artists. Although it was only the talented few who benefited from this, it did create a growing middle class—one that now suffers under Galina’s reign. The diversion of funds to the military build-up resulted in many intellectuals losing their livelihoods, and when they protested this and the resumption of universal conscription, they became the targets of a purge. Many of the artists and scientists who were once drawn to Victovy have now fled the country, and most of those who remain are sheltered by boyars who exploit their work. A few have begun to form a resistance movement, and are now hunted by the Tsarina’s secret police.</span></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-indent:.25in\"><span class=\"RPGMaterial\"><span style=\"mso-ansi-font-size:12.0pt\">Despite these purges and persecutions, the new government’s propaganda campaigns have led to a resurgence of militaristic fervor, convincing the average citizen that Victovy is surrounded by jealous enemies who are simultaneously powerful enough to threaten the empire, and weak enough that a glorious victory is assured. This combination has led to the desired result of mass enlistment in Galina’s growing army.</span></span></p>","folder":null,"sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"hsFJxrWN4M5Ezw3L":3},"flags":{"core":{"sourceId":"Compendium.aetrimonde_v0_8_x.aetrimonde-setting.zrLpOtSLsUWptEui"},"cf":{"id":"temp_i4cc68g5ub","path":"The World of Aetrimonde#/CF_SEP/Major Polities","color":"#000000"}}}
